    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - LIFT AXLE SYSTEMS - FIXED (RIGID) AXLE ASSEMBLIES</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec id="hl14019050">
        <title>FIXED (RIGID) AXLE ASSEMBLIES</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="0">
            <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
            <para>Fixed lift axles do not allow the wheels to steer while cornering. This causes increased tire wear
                (compared to a self-steering axle) due to tire scrubbing while cornering, but it allows the axle design
                to be simple, requiring less maintenance. The fixed axle currently used has a 20,000 pound capacity and
                may be used as either a tag axle or a single pusher axle.
            </para>
            <para>Some features of the fixed lift axle are:</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>20,000 pound maximum load capacity</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>a rubber bushed two pin axle connection</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>10 inches of axle travel (7 up/3 down)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>cast hub-piloted wheel ends</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>integral air tank</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>standard hubs and drums are cast 10 hole - 11.25in bc unimount</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>standard brakes system includes 16.5x7 Meritor Q-Plus brakes, Type 30 MGM chambers, 931 - 162
                        Federal Mogul brake linings, and a Meritor slack adjuster
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
